{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17520036","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17520036"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:19:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13134"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13134"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.72,0.06,0.02,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5571"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102407"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5571"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13134"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84878"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"317"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6275"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9465"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11034"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14895"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15110"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34850"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34851"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42852"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44882"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102407"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of increased confusion. Her husband reports that she fell yesterday with a fall onto the lawn, however protected herself by rolling. Initially, she did not experience any symptoms after the fall, but over the following day, she became more lethargic and confused. She has a medical history of hyperlipidaemia and underwent a right total hip replacement five weeks ago, complicated by a deep vein thrombosis (DVT) two weeks postoperatively. Her regular medications are warfarin and atorvastatin. Two weeks ago, her international normalised ratio (INR) was 2.7 (2-3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears confused with a GCS of 14. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. She has slurred speech and is oriented to person, but not to place or time. Neurological examination is otherwise normal. The rest of the physical examination is unremarkable. A head CT scan is ordered.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely underlying pathophysiology of this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clot formation in the middle meningeal artery","Tearing of the bridging veins","Ruptured aneurysm","Hypertensive hemorrhage","Diffuse axonal injury"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the absence of focal neurological deficits and the patient\u0027s history of recent trauma and anticoagulation therapy, the most plausible explanation is a traumatic brain injury with an acute subdural hematoma due to \u003Cstrong\u003Etearing of the bridging veins\u003C/strong\u003E. The altered mental status and slurred speech could be attributed to the effects of the expanding hematoma on the brain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture in this case is most suggestive of a subacute subdural haematoma in view of the anticoagulation and her recent fall and one day of lucidity. This is the result of the trauma causing tearing of the bridging veins, which connect the cortical superficial veins to the sagittal sinus in the dura. This blood will slowly extravasate into the subdural space, but in this case was hastened by the anticoagulation. The patient\u0027s fall was recorded one day prior to admission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClot formation in the middle meningeal artery\u003C/strong\u003E would typically be associated with an extradural haematoma, which is usually caused by trauma resulting in a skull fracture. This patient\u0027s history of a head strike on a soft surface is less likely to be consistent with an extradural haematoma. There is no evidence of a skull fracture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERuptured aneurysms\u003C/strong\u003E often present with a sudden, severe headache described as \u0022the worst headache of my life.\u0022 While the patient does have confusion and lethargy, the history and presentation are less suggestive of a ruptured aneurysm.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertensive haemorrhage\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in patients with chronic hypertension and often presents with focal neurological deficits, such as hemiparesis or hemisensory loss. The patient\u0027s neurological examination did not reveal a focal motor neurological deficit, which makes hypertensive haemorrhage less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiffuse axonal injury\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs in the context of high-velocity trauma and often leads to widespread damage throughout the brain. The patient\u0027s history of a low-velocity fall onto a soft surface is not consistent with diffuse axonal injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most acute subdural hematomas (ASDHs) develop after rupture of a bridging vein or veins - the anatomy of the bridging vein predisposes to its tearing within the border cell layer of the dura mater.","A subdural hematoma, as its name implies, forms as an abnormal collection of blood under the dura mater."],"references":["Pierre L, Kondamudi NP. Subdural Hematoma. IIn: StatPearls [Online]. Updated 2023 Apr 3. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK532970/","Miller JD, Nader R. Acute subdural hematoma from bridging vein rupture: a potential mechanism for growth. J Neurosurg. 2014 Jun;120(6):1378-84. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24313607/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84878"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13134"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84878"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-12T10:45:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-12T10:46:36+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5571"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102407"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attribute